Anonymous Thu 02 Jul 2020 23:15:35 No.31267485 Report
Quoted By: >>31269887
>>31266797
As I said, I wrote that in line at a drive-thru therefor it's probably shoddy. I was specifically referring to dialogue tagging in my advice. A new sentence after a tag should be capitalized, I have no idea where you got it that I implied otherwise. What I was trying to get across is twofold: when you do a tag you should be making part of the dialogue sentence, and the essence of the rules around punctuation in tagging. Examples of improper tagging:
>"I made you a cake, Anon!" She said.
>"I made you a cake, Anon." She said.
>"I made you a cake, Anon..." She said.
>"I made you a cake, Anon." she said.
Those are all wrong. The following are right.
>"I made you a cake, Anon," she said.
>"I made you a cake, Anon!" she said.
>"I made you a cake, Anon..." she said.

Any sentences after the period on the tagged sentence should be capitalized. I won't get into the debate on whether you should end a paragraph with closed dialogue or if you can add a sentence or two afterward.

However, when you close a sentence in dialogue, put a beat in, then open new dialogue quote without tagging there's no problem. It's up to debate how long that beat should be, but something like this works just fine and is a good example of the function:
>"Anon you sure like cake." She poked him in the stomach. "You like it too much, I'd say."
You can also mix an action in with a tag instead of creating new sentences. As a matter of economy of story telling. Example:
>"You're lucky I like your dad bod," she said, prodding him in the gut.

Anonymous Fri 03 Jul 2020 02:49:42 No.31271461 Report
Quoted By:
>>31269887
>Standard sentence-terminating marks are still needed when using them to indicate a trail-off.
That's not exactly correct; it's not a strictly defined thing in English itself, and depends on the house style. Some consider ellipsis when used for trailing thoughts to be a valid terminator and some do not, though all guides I've ever had to use agreed that ellipsis used to indicate omission at the end of a quote would always require the further period - though that in turn can vary with different house styles about spacing it "... ." or "...." etc.; I think a lot of journalistic style guides insist on the former spacing pattern as it makes a difference to the nature of the omission if you see ". ..." or "... ." in the middle of a quote.
tl;dr when writing for yourself, you can do whichever makes you feel most comfortable for trailing thought ellipsis.
